st[int], nums2: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def xorAllNums(self, nums1: List[int], nums2: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Initialize the result\n        result = 0\n        \n        # If nums2 is of odd length, XOR all elements of nums1\n        if len(nums2) % 2 == 1:\n            for num in nums1:\n                result ^= num\n        \n        # If nums1 is of odd length, XOR all elements of nums2\n        if len(nums1) % 2 == 1:\n            for num in nums2:\n                result ^= num\n        \n        return result\n```\n\n### Explanation:\nThe key insight here is to recognize that each element in `nums1` will be XORed with each element in `nums2` exactly once. The result of XORing all pairings can be simplified based on the parity (odd or even) of the lengths of `nums1` and `nums2`.\n\n- If the length of `nums2` is odd, each element in `nums1` will appear an odd number of times in the final XOR result (since it is paired with each element in `nums2`).\n- Similarly, if the length of `nums1` is odd, each element in `nums2` will appear an odd number of times in the final XOR result.\n- If both lengths are even, every element will appear an even number of times, and thus the result will be 0 (since XORing a number with itself an even number of times results in 0).\n\nThis solution efficiently computes the result in O(n + m) time complexity, where n and m are the lengths of `nums1` and `nums2`, respectively.", "estimated_date": 1664064000000}